rch on Scotland's rural economy and society.Early modern Scotland was predominantly rural. Agriculture was the main occupation of most people at the time, so what happened in the countryside was crucial: economically, socially and culturally. The essays collected here focus on the years between around 1500 and 1750. This period, although before the main era of agricultural "improvement" in the late eighteenth and early nineteenth centuries, was nevertheless far from static in terms of agrarian development. Specific topics addressed include everyday farming practices; investment; landlords, tenants and estate management; and the cultural context within which agriculture was "imagined". The disastrous famine of 1622-23 is analysed in detail. The volume is completed by a comprehensive survey of recent historiography, setting agricultural history in its broader context.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAgriculturezScotlandxHistory. 0aFarm tenancyzScotlandxHistory. 4aEarly Modern History. 4aSocial History. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 17th Century.2bisacsh  aAgricultural History.  aAgricultural Revolution.  aLinlithgowshire.  aLowland clearances.  aMercantilist Age.  aScottish Highlands.  aScottish famine.  aShetland.  aStriling.  aTithes.  aearly modern Scotland.  aenclosure.  arural economy.1 aCarlin, Norah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCornell, Harriet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCornell, Harriet, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGoodare, Julian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoodare, Julian, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHall, Kevin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarrison, Joh